[1] Ecuador (El Oro)
Date: Thu 18 Mar 2010
Source: BBC Mundo [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.bbc.co.uk/mundo/ciencia_tecnologia/2010/03/100311_2327_ecuador_dengue_gm.shtml>


Ecuador has registered an increased increment in
dengue cases so far this year [2010] in relation
to totals for the same period in 2009. The
Subsecretary of Health for the Costa Insular
region, Marcelo Aguilar, said to BBC Mundo that
up until now in the country, especially in the
coastal provinces, 3985 dengue cases have been
treated, which represents 3.5 times more than
were detected in the 1st 10 weeks in the previous
year [2009]. Of these, this year [2010] there
have been a total of 78 DHF cases, the
[clinically] most lethal variety of the disease.
Subsecretary Aguillar indicated that just one
dengue death has been confirmed in the country
and added that the Ministry of Health is working
to prevent high indices of death caused by
[dengue virus] transmitted by the _Aedes aegypti_
mosquito vector of the disease [virus]. The
official said that sanitary actions to combat the
mosquito could extend until June.

The increase in the number of dengue cases has
been caused, according to Aguillar, by "climatic
anomalies" which have affected Ecuadorian coastal
zones, such as an increase in temperature up to 3
degrees [C, 5.4F] above usual levels, as well as
high environmental humidity, "which generate
extraordinary conditions for the reproduction of
the mosquito." The proliferation of _Aedes
aegypti_ moreover, has been facilitated by
deficient sanitary conditions in various areas of
the country. "Problems with trash collection and
water management, as well as the lack of basic
infrastructure, create constant conditions which
produce dengue outbreaks," indicated Aguillar.

El Oro province, on the south Coast of Ecuador,
has been most affected by the presence of dengue
in the country. In this province, on the border
of Peru, up to now has registered 2042 classical
dengue cases and 46 of DHF, and have established
epidemiological barriers there through fumigation
that permit combat against the mosquito that
transmits the disease [virus].

The Director of the Teofilo Davila Hospital, the
main one of the province, Jose Ojeda, indicated
to BBC Mundo that the high dengue incidence in El
Oro is related to public health problems and lack
of public health education of the population.
"Cities, when they undergo unorganized increases
with the lack of basic services such as provision
of potable water and trash collection, and with
inadequate waste water drainage, are exposed to
the proliferation of diverse diseases such as
dengue," said the Director. However, Ojeda stated
that the impact of dengue is being offset by
action by health organizations and the community.
"If we were not prepared to confront this
disease, perhaps many more would have died among
those infected with DHF," he concluded.

--
