[2] Brazil (Rio de Janeiro)
Date: 18 Mar 2010
Fuente: SciDev.Net [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.scidev.net/en/news/building-construction-waste-increases-dengue-rates-.html>


In urban areas, the housing boom with the
consequent generation of waste materials, could
contribute of the increase in the number of
dengue cases, according to a pioneering study
done in Rio de Janeiro, published recently in the
journal Waste Management [Sampaio, A.M.M. /
Kligerman, D.C. / Junior, S.F. 2009, Dengue,
related to rubble and building construction in
Brazil, Waste Management, 29 (11), p.2867-2873,
in English].

The mosquito _Aedes aegypti_, transmitter of
dengue [viruses] reproduce where there is water
collection. Because of that, the accumulation of
trash in illegal areas or their incorrect
storage, make possible the accumulation of rain
water which leads, as a consequence, to
proliferation of the mosquito.

The Jacarepagua neighborhood which currently has
the greatest increase in the rate of construction
of buildings and condominiums was the highest in
[dengue] incidence. On the other hand, the the
districts in south Rio, such as Copacabana for
example, where the urbanization is more
consolidated and there is less construction, they
have had a lesser [dengue infection] rate. It was
surprising that the prevalence of the [dengue]
epidemic was not more intense in the poorest
neighborhoods of the city, rather it was those
that had the greatest quantity of trash,
underscored Sampaio. These results reinforce the
necessity of correctly handling remains of
materials generated by the construction industry.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-ESP
<promed-esp@promedmail.org>

[In the emerging economies of South America, the
construction industry is that which is most
dynamic and progressive. New apartment buildings
and condominiums are being erected constantly,
although the buildings do not always meet the
norms for safety and hygiene. On the other hand,
owner-construction of housing without respect to
the norms cited previously is the rule, rather
than the exception, particularly in the marginal
slums of the large cities. The recent disasters
in Haiti and Chile bring about intense
reconstruction efforts for new housing, which
also highlight the importance of this report, in
which in addition to describing the potential
problem, propose alternatives to at least
alleviate the problem. Now it is the turn of the
local authorities to make sure that the norms are
strictly complied with and to honor their
responsibility. - Mod.JG]

