[3] Brazil (Santos, Sao Paulo)
Date: Sat 20 Mar 2010
Source: O Globo [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://oglobo.globo.com/cidades/mat/2010/03/20/exames-comprovam-epidemia-de-dengue-em-santos-litoral-paulista-916127507.asp>


Announcement of the test results this Friday [19
Mar 2010], issued by the Instituto Adolfo Lutz,
stated that Santos is living through a dengue
epidemic. The city on the Sao Paulo Coast,
exceeded the level that kept it in an outbreak
situation; now there are 163 confirmed cases per
100 000 inhabitants. The limit for a municipality
with more than 250 000 residents -- Santos has
417 000 -- to be outside an epidemic status is
100 cases per 100 000 population. Up to now,
Santos officially registered a total of 680 cases.

The municipal Secretary of Health, Od√≠lio
Rodrigues Filho, has now announced a new measure:
starting now, all the municipal or private
hospitals and medical units must dispense with
laboratory tests (serological) to detect the
occurrence of dengue [virus infections]. For
example, it will be sufficient for physicians to
use clinical-epidemiological criteria. If the
[health] professional verifies that the patients
presents with a clinical picture that is
suspicious [of dengue virus infection], it will
be considered a confirmed case, explained
Rodrigues Filho. Another measure cited by
Rodrigues Filho was the suspension of the
[appointment] schedules for Basic Health Units
(BHUs). We adopted free demand [attention].
Whoever comes with [dengue] symptoms will be seen.

--
