[5] Brazil (Distrito Federal)
Date: Wed 17 Mar 2010
Source: Correio Braziliense [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.correiobraziliense.com.br/app/noticia182/2010/03/17/cidades,i=180199/ESSA+E+A+PIOR+EPIDEMIA+DE+DENGUE+DA+HISTORIA.shtml>


The Secretariat of Health admitted that the
[current] number of cases of the disease[dengue]
in the Distrito Federal [Federal District, DF]
has never been registered previously. There are
now 1956 confirmed [cases], 415 more than the
previous week [week of 7 Mar 2010]. The
government also recognizes that the [case]
statistics could be underreported.

The Distrito Federal is living through its worst
epidemic of all time. These are the words of the
Subsecretary of Health Surveillance, Alan Kardec.
Yesterday [16 Mar 2010], The Secretariat of
Health announced that there are now 1956
confirmed dengue cases, a number 1503 percent
more than at the beginning of last year [2009].
Given this increase in statistics, technical
personnel in the health sector researched health
surveys done in previous years and not found
similar situations. "We are alarmed," admits
Kardec.

To combat the problem, a crisis cabinet, before
with Subsecretariat administered by Kardec, is
now under the command by the Secretary of Health
Joaquim Barros, starting as of next Tuesday [23
Mar 2010]. The Secretariat of Health also
discussed carrying out a day of awareness for the
fight against dengue. On that date, which will be
scheduled for the beginning or mid-April, the
press will be called, pamphlets will be
distributed and mobilizations are planned in
communities. According to an advisor to the
Subsecretariat of Health, Aiton Domicio da Silva,
what is most serious at the moment is the number
of confirmed registered [cases] and that the
disease has spread to various regions of the
Distrito Federal. "The situation is not out of
control, but it is worrying," he stated.

The picture could be even more serious than the
official numbers demonstrate. According to
Subsecretary Allan Kardec, the number of ill
people [with dengue] could be an underestimate
due to underreporting, that is to say, infected
people and even [health] posts and hospitals are
not reporting the data for health services to
Environmental Surveillance.

Of the 11 deaths that might have been related to
dengue, 2 were confirmed [as dengue], 4 were
discarded [not dengue-related] and 5 continue
under investigation. The region in which has the
greatest concentration of [dengue case] reports
continues to be Asa Norte, including Vila
Planalto, with 588 confirmed cases. Planaltina is
in 2nd place, with 299 cases. [Others include]
Planaltina - 299, Itapoa - 256, Sao Sebastiao -
127, Paranoa - 99 and Guara - 87 [cases].

[In summary] the scale of the disease [outbreak]
is 4294 suspected [dengue] cases in all of the
DF, 1956 confirmed cases.

--
