[6] Paraguay
Date: Fri 19 Mar 2010
Source: VoaNews [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www1.voanews.com/spanish/news/latin-america/Paraguay-tres-muertes-por-dengue---88636742.html>


Of the 1191 [dengue] cases, there are now 3
deaths and there are 300 hospitalized patients,
according to health authorities. They recommend
that those who have dengue symptoms do not travel
during Easter Week. Paraguay is suffering the
impact of dengue with more than 1191 ill
individuals and 3 patients who died, according to
the announcement by Ivan Allende, Director of the
Office of Sanitary Surveillance of the Ministry
of Public Health. This epidemiological outbreak
began in December [2009], according to the
office, and since then the number increased to
1191 cases. To date, moreover, there are about
300 hospitalized patients and 11 serious cases.
The Paraguay Ministry of Public Health is
carrying out a campaign for dengue eradication in
the areas most affected in the country, such as
the Alto Parana department [state of province
equivalent], where there are more than 500
patients with dengue symptoms, and the Amabay
department.

Allende recommended that Paraguayans with
dengue-related symptoms not travel "to not place
at risk the population in the interior of the
country," according to statements by the Ministry
of Public Health. At Easter Week there is usually
a "spike" of the epidemic, "which reflects the
outbreaks within the country," Allende said. "One
of the recommendations is not to travel with
fever or symptoms of dengue, because it may put
at risk the population of other districts," he
said.

Paraguay has had the [dengue] epidemic for 6
months, and "it is very intense," he stated.

--
