[7] Bolivia
Date: Fri 19 Mar 2010
Source: Xinhua [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://spanish.peopledaily.com.cn/31614/6924941.html>


The latest report from the National
Epidemiological Unit issued on 18 [Mar 2010]
shows that there are now 24 municipalities with
dengue present in 7 of the 9 departments [state
or province equivalents] in Bolivia. The
epidemiological section of the Ministry of Health
stated, moreover, that to date there are 266
laboratory confirmed [dengue] cases and 2586
suspected [cases], as well as maintaining an
"alarm zone" in this Andean country before
declaring an epidemic.

"We have had a marked increase since Friday of
the previous week [12 Mar 2010] 100 - 150 samples
have begun to come in [to the laboratory for
dengue testing]. And so this says that generally
the physicians, when a patient comes in with a
fever, they think it is dengue and send in
[samples] for rule-outs," said the Director of
the National Center for Tropical Disease
(CENETROP), Jorge Vargas.

In turn, the head of the regional program of
diseases transmitted by vectors of the
Epidemiological Unit, Juan Calos Arraya,
explained the the [dengue virus] incursion into
the "alarm zone" is determined based on dengue
behavior in the last 5-7 years. The exception is
2009 because this was an epidemic year with more
than 40 000 cases and nearly 50 deaths. "Always,
each year there are outbreaks and their magnitude
varies from year to year; in 2010 we can say that
we have a mild outbreak in relation to last year.
Dengue has to do with the rains, due to the
accumulation of fresh water and are places where
[the mosquito vector] deposits its eggs," stated
Vargas.

He stated that of all the samples that come into
CENETROP, 10 - 15 percent are positive [for
dengue].

"In places where cases are appearing, SEDES
(Departmental Health Services) are fumigating,
[mounting] campaigns so that people do not
accumulate water and a national alarm does not
exist. We will see how it goes next week," he
explained.

According to Health [Ministry] reports, there are
approximately 20-25 [new] cases each day. "We do
not predict a dengue epidemic -- everything is
under control. Yes, a small dengue outbreak
exists and will be controlled; in comparison with
last year [2009], we are far away [from a similar
epidemic]," stated Arraya.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed-port@promedmail.org>

[It is always risky to say, "everything is under
control," when diseases such as dengue can cause
sudden, explosive outbreaks or epidemics, and
control of the vector is so difficult and often
ineffective. It would be of interest to know
which dengue virus serotypes of the 4 is
circulating in Bolivia currently. This report
does not indicate which of 7 of the 9 departments
has confirmed dengue cases. Presumably
transmission is occurring in those departments
that have areas within in the tropical Amazon
Basin, and especially Santa Cruz department which
was especially hard hit in the 2009 epidemic.

[A relief map showing the Amazon Basin east of
the Andes mountains can be accessed at
